Maddie Ford

I love being a Chapel stylist because I feel the way we work around time gives me more time to really connect and get to know my guests.

At The Chapel, we don’t just care for your hair, but you as a person, and your well being. The company also cares for us, as stylists. It’s like being at home and I really look forward to stepping in the doors everyday - it is work, but it doesn’t feel like work.

As a stylist I love to give my guests a fun and vibrant experience. I absolutely love colour and how uplifting it makes people feel.

About Me


I was born in Caracas, Venezuela and moved to Miami in 2007 with my family. I am a fashion blogger with aspirations of becoming a well-known stylist and designer. I am currently enrolled at Savannah College of Art and Design pursuing an M.A. in Luxury and Fashion Management.


I graduated from Florida International University in Spring 2016 with two degrees: a B.S. in Broadcast Media and a B.A. Psychology. While pursuing my undergraduate degrees, I interned for several companies including Ocean Drive Magazine. I was also invited to become a co-founder of the Venezuelan Student Alliance which became my first exposure to a leadership role. I began as events coordinator and made my way up to the presidency of the club. 

As a young girl, I developed an interest in fashion and the arts; something that has influenced me throughout my life. In January 2014, I decided to combine my studies and my passions and created a blog. Moda Addicted is a space where I practice my writing with the purpose of inspiring young women to be their better selves. The fashion and lifestyle blog purpose is to inspire readers, through my outfits and photographs, and tips on how to remain in style and have an enjoyable social life without spending much money on it.


My goals include to become a well-known fashion stylist and to put to practice my luxury management skill and create my own clothing label.

The Image is … produces high profile fashion events in Canada and operates Worldwide.

In the two decades that Hans Koechling has been producing shows for luxury fashion houses, designers and lifestyle brands, he specializes in turn-key services from concept to completion.

He manages every aspect of a runway show and offers industry clients, innovative concepts, state of the art venues, an experienced production team, brand building events and image campaigns that generate maximum exposure.

Coordinating the client’s lead and needs; all details from the creative and show planning, casting, staging, décor, technical production, to executing the event with his team of key experienced production and event specialists, as well as directing the events, campaigns and shows.

As a seasoned producer on multiple platforms, Hans is a rare breed, whose fine-tuned approach and International expertise are widely recognized in the fashion industry. Whether it’s a Designer Show, a Luxury Fashion Exhibition, Art Installation, Beauty Campaign or a Film, clients favor his high professional standards and personal touch, as well as his extensive knowledge and expertise of prime importance in a constantly evolving global fashion world.

His concepts are inspired by his great passion for fashion, history and the arts, music and film, beauty, travel, style, luxury and celebrity. He delivers strong casting, current fashion styling and artistic direction, creating seamless productions, photo-shoots, on-line events and television specials with memorable, powerful eye-catching images.

Along with the passion, planning and adrenaline that go into staging a world-class runway show, his vision encompasses a production with an acute understanding of the technical logistics such as lighting, sound and staging, that bring a show to life.

Serena Da Conceicao



New York native Serena Da Conceicao designed her first garment at the age of five, creating a genie costume. This graduate of the Fashion Institute of Design and Merchandising also received a three-year apprenticeship with a custom leather and bridal design studio. She later got a nomination for an Ecco Domani award while working at CLIFT NYC 2005 or 2006. For work, she was employed as a custom tailor and pattern maker and later became a design apprentice in making leather and lace garments. She soon found herself auditioning for Project Runway and became a contestant in season 9 as one of 20 designers hoping to make it big in the industry.

About me

Hello sweet people!

Welcome to my website. WARNING: this website contains a lot of make-up, make-up and make-up.

My name is Linda Marin Sanchez. Half Dutch, half Spanish living in Holland/England. It was always my dream to become a make-up artist. I didn’t know how or when but it had to happen. 2 years ago I joined make-up school next to my job. Locked myself in my room and watched youtube videos 24/7.  And i got all the questions. The ”how are you going to do this?” the ”What’s your plan?” ”Can you find a ‘real’ job in Make-up?” And i would say with a straight face: ”I will succeed and it will happen. 100% sure.” I often get the sarcastic ”yes, sure you can” or that i souldn’t be so confident/arrogant because it’s not that easy. And that’s true, it’s certainly not easy. But it’s SO worth it.

And now 2 years later i worked with the best brand. Tom Ford, Estee Lauder, Urban Decay, Rotterdam Fashion Week and a lot more. And i’m loving it! Something i didn’t even dare to dream about before. Nothing is more important in life than doing something that makes you happy. And i am lucky enough to say i am a very happy girl!

With this I want to say to everyone who can’t see the light anymore at the end of the tunnel, or for everyone who think they can’t. YOU CAN. I know it’s cliche but if you really want something, you really can.

From now on i want to share my story, my make-up advices, turotials, reviews and my life with you! I hope you will join my journey. And if you have any questions (about everything) please reach out to me!!

Thank you for visiting this website and.. stay tuned!

Tiane Tenui


Tiane Tenui is the culmination of Founder Christiane’s experience within the fashion industry, her deep appreciation for beautiful materials and a tactile exploration in refined simplicity. Exclusively creating custom pieces for each client—every single cut, stitch, tiny internal knot tied or seam sewn is completed by Christiane herself, one single piece at a time, taking however long is needed to create perfection. This is the definition of slow craft.

Christiane Smit has spent years placed firmly within the fashion industry. Beginning at an early age observing her mother making clothing and accompanying her to fabric stores creating objects became second nature. She spent a number of years traveling abroad and engaging with various cultures always searching for treasures; it is a vital part of who she is. Later, working in fashion with Japanese designers, she learned the importance of every last detail and why creating from the very best materials she can find is so instrumental to her ethos.
